description.text:
Update: I included an Autodesk 123D file so you can customize your dowel holes.
Resize the dowel in the 3d file to the right diameter, pattern in a circle around the origin axis I created with 8 copies, and then subtract the dowels from the base.

This is a segmented bottle tree for drying my flip top bottles after cleaning.

The bottle tree this work is based off of has a great base but the arms are flimsy.
I gave up on the printed arms. They are very weak unless you print the thing very solid which takes too much time and plastic. The base and central column are very strong even printed with 10% infill.

By making holes to insert wooden dowels as arms we reduce the print time and reduce plastic, and you can fit multiple arm segments on most print beds. Win win win :D

I used 6.3mm*30cm diameter dowels from the dollar store, cut in half. I you have larger or smaller dowels. you could probably use the scaling function in your slicer to make the holes fit. If you want super high performance, use hollow carbon rods instead! ;)

Enjoy.

description.text:
This is built with 8mm (5/16") wooden dowel sticks

If you want to see more and how I create prints and 3D designs like this check out my YouTube channel.
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCSHUc93NXGwBacoIDDqPU2w
NGSS CCSS

Functional and easy to assemble Catapult This project was created for my daughter to build a catapult for the Grade 6 D&T class. The design was done to be easy to assemble as per the picture provided. She can assemble this herself in about 10 minutes. The bucket will hold something around the size of an marshmallow. it is designed to be adjustable to find which angles will give the best trajectory and distance. accuracy is consistent to within about 60cm at a distance of 10-15m an adult may be needed to assist with initial assembly as depending on your printer holed may need to be drilled out. by moving the 3 cross braces tension can be increased without adding more elastic bands. The one we built could easily take 4 thick elastics, but became hard to pull back and 2 worked fine. The top brace can be changed to adjust the release angle. Between 30 and 45 degrees.

The catapult can be assembled in class with no more difficulty than building a lego structure.
For teachers I am happy to send you the freecad source files if you want to make changes, as long as all changes are shared freely as per this license.

Print all parts.
You will need the 4 feet, left and right are different but as long as assembled the same will work.
You will need 6 cross brace pieces printed.
You will need the 2 upper arm mounts the bucket elastic holder and pivot.
The dowel stick need to be:
4 x 220 mm diagonal arms ( Green )
2 x 350 mm lower rods ( Blue )
7 x 125 mm Foot cross braces and lower elastic holder. ( Brown )
3 x 100 mm pivot and arms for release stop and elastic tensioner. ( Red )
2 x 260 mm for the arm ( Orange )

I wanted to buy an Extruder Controller from Makerbot but they are out of stock. And have told me that they are not likely to get any back into stock soon. So I decide I will make one and find out that three of the components on the board are no longer manufactured! So I decided to redesign the makerbot's extruder board and here is a drop in replacement. It's been designed to be dual steptrude compatible as I have removed the DC motor controller (As the have stop making that chip and upgraded it to a small package version).
It has upgraded Mosfets (again they stopped making the one on the MECV3.6) and have added two more in place of the dc motor controller. And Maxim-ic are stopping production of their thermocouple chip, so that also has been updated. I've added a ATXV12 connector that drives the Mosfets. Currently the connector is rated at 300watts which should allow for more power to be delivered. I've also include the option to either use the on board voltage regulator or 5v from the PSU. I've ugraded the MPU to be a 328 instead of the 168 which gives it more Ram and Flash, thus allowing more hacks to be done to it. I plan on making a PCB run from my local PCB manufacturer. If you want one then shout and I'll see what I can do. A Firmware update will be required.

comments.text: DO NOT wire MOSFETs in parallel to increase power. It will not work (for long). In the real world, no two things happen at exactly the same time. Relevant to this conversation, MOSFETs in parallel will not all turn on at exactly the same moment, which means whichever one turns on first will be handling ALL the power that you thought was being shared across them. Eventually this will cause the MOSFETs to fail. When one fails, then the rest won't be far behind. If they happened to fail in a short, you could have a very dangerous situation.

comments.text: For those SMT devices (looks like some SO-8 and a QFP with slightly finer leads), I've done these many times by hand using a liquid flux method. If you flood the pins with liquid flux first, the solder will just flow onto the pins and pads and not try to form bridges between the pins -- so it's actually quite easy, you can just run solder & iron down the row of pins (first tack down two corners and adjust until it's lined up). We used to use a squeeze bottle with a steel nozzle to dispense the flux (it was just like a horse-sized hypodermic needle but with the end cut off flat) but a small plastic syringe would probably work fine.

title: Filament Spool Holder for up to 11 Pieces (Use "IKEA GRUNDTAL" Towel Holder)

description.text:
A wide range of filaments all in one place and ready for use.

Technical Description:

1) Get your GRUNDTAL towel holder from IKEA (or any anything alike)
2) Mount one of the Wall-Fixation parts to the wall (2 Screws) and make sure it is as perfectly levelled as possible
3) Mount the other Wall-Fixation to the rod
4) Fill the rod with spools. Make sure there is at least 30 mm Space left to the outside, so the spools cannot stick later
5) This is the tricky part. You might want to get some help from another person here: Put the other end of the rod to the already mounted fixation and fasten the screw.
6) Hold the rod as horizontal as possible and mount the other fix with 1 screw into the top hole (use a bubble level or anything alike for this part!)

Comments:

  • One screw will be left over. The reason for this is that you will be able to exchange spools faster (just screw out the rod-screw on the fixation holder side, where that is fixed with only 1 screw and swing the older aside).
  • Depending on your wall you should use wall plugs and therefore position everything before starting to mount.
  • Use 2 of the spacers clips (STL) to hold the spool you want to use in place (otherwise it might get stuck on another spool during the print) and make sure the spool can still roll without being stuck.
  • The IKEA-Set includes 2 rods. The second one is not used.
  • If you should experience problems with spooling, use some lubrication on the inside of the spools.
  • Clip is tolerated for 0.4 mm nozzle
  • Have fun :)

This single-file library here allows you to use my self-made tagging system!
It uses a few "special" variables usable in OpenSCAD (which you can see listed and explained in the top of the file) to create some very dynamic and flexible things together with some "children()" function uses :P

How to use?

Simple!

When modelling something that uses this tagging system, simply prefix any object (or group of objects) with the following command:
tag(["list", "of", "tags"], foreground = true/false) (do NOT place a semicolon afterwards, that will break the parent/child relationship!)

Once tagged you can rotate, transform, resize, basically do whatever you want with the object. It won't break the tags!

IMPORTANT:
Any differences that you want to apply over the whole model - which is the main reason for this system!! - Should /NOT/ be performed with a difference()!!

INSTEAD:
Tag all your "positives" (the things you want to subtract from) with any name you want, like, well: "positive"
Then tag all the "negatives", which will later be subtracted from the others, with a different tag, like "negative"

Once done, you can perform the difference with:
taggedDifference(["positive", "tags"], ["negative", "tags"], foreground = true/false) {
objects();
}

The end result will be the difference of the different tags.

You can also perform unions with taggedUnion (though that IS a bit silly), as well as intersections with "taggedIntersection".
For a full list of functions, just search through the source file.

WHY?
Well, firstly: WHY NOT!

Secondly, and more importantly:
Using this system it allows you to have "global differences", meaning: Things like holes and spaces that will be subtracted /from everything else/
WITHOUT the need to write those down separately!
What's even better is that the tagging works together with all your common tools like translate(), rotate(), mirror(), scale(), resize(), for loops etc. etc.!
So now, having such global differences is easier than ever!

Just over a month in development, is a redesigned dirtbin for the Neato. This is designed using the signature model, but will likely fit the XV series.

Poorly designed inlet that's prone to blockages,
Poorly designed filter that clogs very quickly,
Missing chamfer on the dirt outlet (Filter) making it slightly more difficult to empty the bin.

Have you ever seen one of these videos where a journalist interviews students and adults, asking them to point Iran out on a map? The result is often funny, and so is this game. Over a hundred countries, some of them you never heard about, in a puzzle race. Here is how to make one of the best geography games of all time! See the whole project on
http://www.instructables.com/id/The-World-Puzzle-How-to-learn-your-countries-the/step3/Move-the-parts/

All the instructions are on my instructables : http://www.instructables.com/id/The-World-Puzzle-How-to-learn-your-countries-the/ Many types of materials can be used : wood, cardboard, polypropylene, metal... But I used colored acrylic 0.172 inch thick. The size of the board was 2 x 3 feet (24 x 36 inches), but could be bigger since you can easily scale or edit the .EPS file.
Don't forget to remove the protection layer before doing anything with it. First, you will need to clip (or tape) the board in your laser cutter. (I used an Epilog Legend 36 EXT)
If you don't know your settings perfectly, I suggest you make some tests before sending the real thing to cut.
You will engrave first and then cut. The opposite would result in poor word definition. On the EPS file, everything in black is to engrave and everything in red is to cut using the 'hairline' thickness. When everything is etched and cut, don't TOUCH ANYTHING You will now need to move the puzzle pieces onto cardboard. If you do it straight, some small pieces will fall inside the laser cutter, so I suggest this : Use some wide masking tape to cover all countries. Once that's done, quickly put the cardboard underneath.
Put in a safe place, far from dogs and babies.

We're busy developing the game, Vicious Attack Llama Apocalypse (trailer)

Notes:

The model is split into two parts, with the head model having small tabs that fit under the muzzle model. I uses a generic brand of 2-part epoxy steel to glue it together and it holds very firmly.

The first time I printed this, I did it in ABS and experienced both warping and cracking. Although that didn't matter too much for the look of it, it meant that the parts didn't join together correctly.
So I suggest you do it in PLA or something that doesn't warp.

I used 100% infill because I was worried about cracking, but that leads to a lot of plastic, and with PLA I'm sure you could get away with much less infill.

Print with a raft, and lot's of whatever you use to stick prints to your bed (you don't want a long print like this lifting).

I've only printed one scaled-down version, and the parts do seem to still line up with each other.

Instead of watching my printer while getting close to the end of the roll of filament, I picked up a Low Filament Sensor from EndLessParts.com http://tinyurl.com/j63ecw5 . It’s a fairly simple device that lets out a loud buzzing sound when the end of the filament has passed by it, giving you time to pause the print and change out the filament with a fresh spool. The sensor has two sets of roller bearings that are spring loaded so that when the last of the filament passes through the roller bearings, a contact switch is released by the spring and the buzzer is activated. There is an on/off switch, and from what I can tell, the sensor only uses battery power when the buzzer is sounded.

The sensor comes with four different colored covers and two spacers, one for 1.75mm filament and one for 3mm filament. Mine came with the 1.75mm spacer installed. The sensor is made by a 3D printer and is very strong. The sensor has some double sided foam tape attached to the back of and a couple of ears for using screws, depending on where and how you need to attach it to your printer.

Using the MP Select Mini Filter Bar http://tinyurl.com/Filter-Bar by Jason Jones, I designed with Tinkercad.com a holder for the sensor that slips on the flat part of the filter bar so that I can taker the sensor off or put on as needed. Using the foam tape, I attached the sensor to the holder, I made the holder wide enough incase I need to use some screws.

For a test, I decided to use the sample filament that came with the printer and make the half cat so as to give everyone a sense of how long between the first sound of the buzzer and the end of the filament hits the extruder. In my test, it was 3 minutes and 3 seconds with my setup. The length if time can be increase by having the sensor further from the extruder, depending on you choice of filament holders. For three minutes is more than long enough for my needs from where I sit and where the printer is located. This sensor has made my end of filament life so much easier as I can now do other things besides watching my printer, YMMV

Video of the sensor in action https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iXJPpmCalHo

description.text:
17Feb2017 -- Added mounts for 40x15mm drag chain per qbvbsite's request. I havent tested it or anything, but it seemed to fit his well.

"remix" of ooznet's Y drag chain mount.

Basic dimensions are all the same, except re-drawn from scratch and rounded off. I believe theirs goes the other way (you mount the chain on the bottom), but due to my belt tensioners and stepper, I didnt have room, so i made this.

Added rear mount. This one goes into the end of the 'x' v-slot in 3 ways. It has 'nubs' that go into the slot, Screws also go into the end of the v-slot (youll need an M5 tap), and also attaches with a T-Nut (drop in or regular).

STEP file included so you can modify it and such. Made for a 15x30 drag chain, and the hole pattern kind of matches that. Youll need to drill out the existing holes (M4 sized) to allow an M5 bolt through, or stick with an M4, but you will need to drill a new hole, just forward of the other one, to allow the third bolt through, see pic. Also includes inserts for M5 nuts on the bottom of it, as its kind of hard to get a wrench in there with the supports.

Were all those supports necessary? I dont know, but it feels pretty hefty, so why not?

If you do mount this on the lower holes (right above the stepper like I did), youll need to drill a new hole in the gantry plate to get it in (mine didnt have it at least).

Resolution:

.3mm (or .2mm)

Infill:

comments.text:
What he's saying is that you can't stack fans like this, or at least you're not going to get the effect you expect. if you put the 4 fans side by side, they'll pull 4 times the volume of air. But if you put them in a line, they're all pulling the same volume of air. If you took the 4 side-by-side fans and put a cowling around them and funneled the exhaust down to the size of one fan, the 4 fans wouldn't be able to push 4 times the amount of air out the funnel. these fans aren't good at holding back pressure, so the extra air would slip back around the fan blades out the front.
Another way to think about it is if these were 3 matching water pumps. the first pump pushes water to the second pump. if the second pump pushed water faster to the third pump, the first pump couldn't provide enough water to the second pump to keep the water flowing. at best, they spread the load among three pumps.

I was thinking of a way to remove the Z-axis motor from a RepStrap machine, and instead use the X-axis to ratchet the boom up and down by traveling to its extremetries and \'pushing\' a ratchet mechanism.
Pushing the red frame from one end will turn the captive nut by 90 degrees, pushing the other end turns -90 degrees. This would result in a distance of around 0.3mm travel on a standard M8 thread.
It may also be usable as a mechanical stepper motor with the frame driven by a solenoid and the output geared down to required step rotation. The solenoid should be pulsed one way (or the other) until the frame has reached it\'s limit of travel.
This \'motor\' would be expected to be quite slow and noisy, hence this \'motor\' is refered to as a \'mungomotor\' ;-)
This part is at present theoretical, although I would welcome any comments.
The idea is that this part can be made with hand tools, laser cutter or 3D printer.

remixed_from.title: Customizable Canadian License Plate (All Provinces and Territories)

description.text:
An almost unlimited number of preset combinations (100,000+)

Mix and match State, Slogan and Background Details for 50 States and 6 Districts.
Plus your own text in the Header, Footer and Custom Plate Number

Do you want Alaska to be the Sunshine State with a Bucking Bronco on it I'm not going to stop you and neither is this app.

Use the Postal Abbreviation (CAPITALS) to select the State, Slogan and Background, invalid selections (or boring states like Virginia) will show nothing.

I am not American and my list and images came from Wikipedia and Google Image search I am very sorry if I made a mistake (or missed something). Also there is only so much that is possible some of the plates have been simplified due to available resolution.

This is part of a car costume (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1770501) and the default size is 120mm x 50mm.

Customizable Canadian License Plates (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1781423)

I used a sharpie marker to colour the letters and background.

I used Inkscape and a plugin called paths2openscad (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25036) to convert a blank plate (jpg) to an SCAD file then added the text. It should be easy to duplicate it for another province or state.

How I designed this?

1) Downloaded images of all states from Wikipedia and Image Search
2) Created 2-4 black and white png files for each plate (State Name, State Slogan, Background and Back and white image of the whole plate combined for spacing and sizing)
3) Using Inkscape to OpenSCAD plugin I made SCAD files for ever image (203)
4) The rest was easier. I put it all in one huge file and worked through every state starting with the overall image I placed the three components.

Took me about a week in my spare time.

description.text: I designed this magical circle for use with my True Tiles dungeon. I wanted to go for a geometric look inspired by Pythagorean and Hermetic traditions, with clean lines and simple symbols, to fit with a module I am running that takes place in a Roman inspired city. This is meant to appear as smooth inlay in a stone floor suitable for a ritual circle, or focal point for a desk or dais in a magical study.

Notes:

I usually print these with a brim to aid in the adhesion of the first several layers.

I recommend a light sanding around the edges where the print was attached to the brim. The sample piece shown was primed in black, then given a light coat of bone white. It was highlighted with white, and the circle tiles and symbols were painted in their respective colors. After allowing drying time a shade of Citadel Nuln Oil was applied. Clear coating is not necessary, as the PLA takes acrylic very well and anything capable of scratching it off would likely necessitate a new piece anyway. If you feel you must clear coat, I recommend Testors Dullcote.
